{"formatVersion":"1","manifest":{"sourceId":"gibranProphet","displayName":"The Prophet (Kahlil Gibran)","type":"quotes","language":"English","edition":"Kahlil Gibran, 1923 (Public Domain)","primaryCategory":"Poetry & Literature","subcategory":"Spiritual Literature","audienceTags":["literature","reflection"],"sortPriority":54,"itemCount":30,"supportsRandom":true,"supportsBrowse":true,"browseOrder":"sequence","groupingLevels":["chapter"],"groupingLabels":["Chapter"],"dataPath":"Data/Collections/Gibran_Prophet.json","version":"1.0"},"data":[{"id":"prophet-1","text":"When love beckons to you, follow him, though his ways are hard and steep.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet — On Love","tags":["poetry","philosophy","spirituality","language:english","collection:prophet"],"groups":{"chapter":"On Love"},"sequenceIndex":0},{"id":"prophet-2","text":"Love gives naught but itself and takes naught but from itself. Love possesses not nor would it be possessed; for love is sufficient unto love.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet — On Love","tags":["poetry","philosophy","spirituality","language:english","collection:prophet"],"groups":{"chapter":"On Love"},"sequenceIndex":1},{"id":"prophet-3","text":"When you love you should not say, 'God is in my heart,' but rather, 'I am in the heart of God.'","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet — On Love","tags":["poetry","philosophy","spirituality","language:english","collection:prophet"],"groups":{"chapter":"On Love"},"sequenceIndex":2},{"id":"prophet-4","text":"Think not you can direct the course of love, for love, if it finds you worthy, directs your course.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet — On Love","tags":["poetry","philosophy","spirituality","language:english","collection:prophet"],"groups":{"chapter":"On Love"},"sequenceIndex":3},{"id":"prophet-5","text":"You were born together, and together you shall be forevermore. You shall be together when the white wings of death scatter your days.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet — On Marriage","tags":["poetry","philosophy","spirituality","language:english","collection:prophet"],"groups":{"chapter":"On Marriage"},"sequenceIndex":4},{"id":"prophet-6","text":"Love one another, but make not a bond of love. Let it rather be a moving sea between the shores of your souls.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet — On Marriage","tags":["poetry","philosophy","spirituality","language:english","collection:prophet"],"groups":{"chapter":"On Marriage"},"sequenceIndex":5},{"id":"prophet-7","text":"Your children are not your children. They are the sons and daughters of Life's longing for itself.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet — On Children","tags":["poetry","philosophy","spirituality","language:english","collection:prophet"],"groups":{"chapter":"On Children"},"sequenceIndex":6},{"id":"prophet-8","text":"You may give them your love but not your thoughts, for they have their own thoughts. You may house their bodies but not their souls.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet — On Children","tags":["poetry","philosophy","spirituality","language:english","collection:prophet"],"groups":{"chapter":"On Children"},"sequenceIndex":7},{"id":"prophet-9","text":"It is well to give when asked, but it is better to give unasked, through understanding.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet — On Giving","tags":["poetry","philosophy","spirituality","language:english","collection:prophet"],"groups":{"chapter":"On Giving"},"sequenceIndex":8},{"id":"prophet-10","text":"You give but little when you give of your possessions. It is when you give of yourself that you truly give.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet — On Giving","tags":["poetry","philosophy","spirituality","language:english","collection:prophet"],"groups":{"chapter":"On Giving"},"sequenceIndex":9},{"id":"prophet-11","text":"Work is love made visible.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet — On Work","tags":["poetry","philosophy","spirituality","language:english","collection:prophet"],"groups":{"chapter":"On Work"},"sequenceIndex":10},{"id":"prophet-12","text":"And all work is empty save when there is love; and when you work with love you bind yourself to yourself, and to one another, and to God.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet — On Work","tags":["poetry","philosophy","spirituality","language:english","collection:prophet"],"groups":{"chapter":"On Work"},"sequenceIndex":11},{"id":"prophet-13","text":"Your joy is your sorrow unmasked. And the selfsame well from which your laughter rises was oftentimes filled with your tears.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet — On Joy and Sorrow","tags":["poetry","philosophy","spirituality","language:english","collection:prophet"],"groups":{"chapter":"On Joy and Sorrow"},"sequenceIndex":12},{"id":"prophet-14","text":"The deeper that sorrow carves into your being, the more joy you can contain.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet — On Joy and Sorrow","tags":["poetry","philosophy","spirituality","language:english","collection:prophet"],"groups":{"chapter":"On Joy and Sorrow"},"sequenceIndex":13},{"id":"prophet-15","text":"You shall be free indeed when your days are not without a care nor your nights without a want and a grief.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet — On Freedom","tags":["poetry","philosophy","spirituality","language:english","collection:prophet"],"groups":{"chapter":"On Freedom"},"sequenceIndex":14},{"id":"prophet-16","text":"Your soul is oftentimes a battlefield, upon which your reason and your judgment wage war against your passion and your appetite.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet — On Reason and Passion","tags":["poetry","philosophy","spirituality","language:english","collection:prophet"],"groups":{"chapter":"On Reason and Passion"},"sequenceIndex":15},{"id":"prophet-17","text":"Your pain is the breaking of the shell that encloses your understanding.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet — On Pain","tags":["poetry","philosophy","spirituality","language:english","collection:prophet"],"groups":{"chapter":"On Pain"},"sequenceIndex":16},{"id":"prophet-18","text":"Your hearts know in silence the secrets of the days and the nights. But your ears thirst for the sound of your heart's knowledge.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet — On Self-Knowledge","tags":["poetry","philosophy","spirituality","language:english","collection:prophet"],"groups":{"chapter":"On Self-Knowledge"},"sequenceIndex":17},{"id":"prophet-19","text":"Your friend is your needs answered. He is your field which you sow with love and reap with thanksgiving.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet — On Friendship","tags":["poetry","philosophy","spirituality","language:english","collection:prophet"],"groups":{"chapter":"On Friendship"},"sequenceIndex":18},{"id":"prophet-20","text":"You talk when you cease to be at peace with your thoughts.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet — On Talking","tags":["poetry","philosophy","spirituality","language:english","collection:prophet"],"groups":{"chapter":"On Talking"},"sequenceIndex":19},{"id":"prophet-21","text":"And if you would know God, be not therefore a solver of riddles. Rather look about you and you shall see Him playing with your children.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet — On Time","tags":["poetry","philosophy","spirituality","language:english","collection:prophet"],"groups":{"chapter":"On Time"},"sequenceIndex":20},{"id":"prophet-22","text":"Of the good in you I can speak, but not of the evil. For what is evil but good tortured by its own hunger and thirst?","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet — On Good and Evil","tags":["poetry","philosophy","spirituality","language:english","collection:prophet"],"groups":{"chapter":"On Good and Evil"},"sequenceIndex":21},{"id":"prophet-23","text":"God listens not to your words save when He Himself utters them through your lips.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet — On Prayer","tags":["poetry","philosophy","spirituality","language:english","collection:prophet"],"groups":{"chapter":"On Prayer"},"sequenceIndex":22},{"id":"prophet-24","text":"Beauty is not in the face; beauty is a light in the heart.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet — On Beauty","tags":["poetry","philosophy","spirituality","language:english","collection:prophet"],"groups":{"chapter":"On Beauty"},"sequenceIndex":23},{"id":"prophet-25","text":"Beauty is life when life unveils her holy face. But you are life and you are the veil. Beauty is eternity gazing at itself in a mirror.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet — On Beauty","tags":["poetry","philosophy","spirituality","language:english","collection:prophet"],"groups":{"chapter":"On Beauty"},"sequenceIndex":24},{"id":"prophet-26","text":"For life and death are one, even as the river and the sea are one.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet — On Death","tags":["poetry","philosophy","spirituality","language:english","collection:prophet"],"groups":{"chapter":"On Death"},"sequenceIndex":25},{"id":"prophet-27","text":"You would know the secret of death. But how shall you find it unless you seek it in the heart of life?","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet — On Death","tags":["poetry","philosophy","spirituality","language:english","collection:prophet"],"groups":{"chapter":"On Death"},"sequenceIndex":26},{"id":"prophet-28","text":"What is it to die but to stand naked in the wind and to melt into the sun? And when the earth shall claim your limbs, then shall you truly dance.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet — On Death","tags":["poetry","philosophy","spirituality","language:english","collection:prophet"],"groups":{"chapter":"On Death"},"sequenceIndex":27},{"id":"prophet-29","text":"A little while, a moment of rest upon the wind, and another woman shall bear me.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet — The Coming of the Ship","tags":["poetry","philosophy","spirituality","language:english","collection:prophet"],"groups":{"chapter":"The Coming of the Ship"},"sequenceIndex":28},{"id":"prophet-30","text":"Forget not that I shall come back to you. A little while, and my longing shall gather dust and foam for another body.","author":"Kahlil Gibran","source":"The Prophet — The Farewell","tags":["poetry","philosophy","spirituality","language:english","collection:prophet"],"groups":{"chapter":"The Farewell"},"sequenceIndex":29}]}